article.headline: KG and Wally find helper in deadeye Hudson
article.linkText: Third wheel Hudson helps steer Wolves past Hornets
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Minnesota Timberwolves opponents always try to stop Kevin Garnett and Wally Szczerbiak right away.
 
Hudson
They better start looking out for Troy Hudson. Hudson hit four 3-pointers in the first quarter and scored 22 points to lead Minnesota to a 114-93 win over the New Orleans Hornets on Friday night. "Troy is amazing early,'' Timberwolves coach Flip Saunders said. "What happens is they focus so much on stopping KG and Szczerbiak that it leaves Troy the ability to open up.'' He's been doing just that with the Timberwolves. In his first season as a regular starter, Hudson is gaining a reputation for quick starts. He said he takes the same approach as a starter that he did coming off the bench in Orlando. "When you come off the bench, you have to be aggressive,'' Hudson said. "When the game starts, I take it as if I'm coming off the bench and I do the same thing.'' Garnett had 23 points and eight rebounds in three quarters. The Timberwolves hit a season-high 12 of 19 shots from 3-point range (63 percent) in earning their 15th win in 19 games and 11th in a row at home. But it was Hudson's play early that kept New Orleans at bay. "I got a couple 3s to go down for me early,'' Hudson said. "I kept shooting until I missed.'' David Wesley scored 21 points for the Hornets, including 15 in the first quarter on 7-of-10 shooting. "Wesley was great tonight,'' Saunders said. "The biggest thing was we didn't get caught up in that.'' Hudson scored 12 and Garnett had 10 points and five rebounds in the first quarter as the Wolves grabbed a 37-29 lead. After his big start, Wesley didn't make another shot until 8:18 of the third quarter, and the Timberwolves built a 64-52 lead. "They really shot it well,'' Hornets coach Paul Silas said. "They gave us a good spanking.'' The Hornets have struggled on offense since the All-Star break. In three games before the break, New Orleans averaged more than 100 points and shot almost 50 percent from the field and 3-point range. In three games after the break, the Hornets have averaged just 81 points. They have yet to shoot over 42 percent from the field or over 20 percent from 3-point range. Silas said Wesley's fast start gave the Hornets hope, but Hudson's first quarter ensured the momentum stayed on Minnesota's side. "Hudson is streaky,'' New Orleans guard Robert Pack said. "But you know any game he can give you that. He was feeling it and had it going. It's going to be tough to stop him when he's like that.'' Hudson calmed down after the first quarter, and Szczerbiak took over in the second half. After scoring just two points in the first half, Szczerbiak led a nine-point scoring burst at the end of the third quarter that put away the Hornets. His jumper with 9:45 left in the game gave the Wolves a 95-72 lead and capped a 15-2 run, allowing Garnett to rest the entire fourth quarter for the first time all season. "I'll take rest over any double-double and any of the personal accolades,'' said Garnett, the MVP of Sunday's All-Star game. "Rest is always good. Rest is not a bad thing.'' Szczerbiak finished with 18 points, seven rebounds and six assists. Jamal Mashburn had 19 points on 8-of-23 shooting and seven rebounds for New Orleans.

Game notes
Hornets F P.J. Brown missed the game while attending the funeral of a family member on his wife's side. Silas said he's expected to return to the lineup Sunday against Denver. ... Friday's game featured two of the four players in the NBA who average at least 20 points, six rebounds and five assists _ Garnett and Mashburn. The other two are Sacramento's Chris Webber and the Lakers' Kobe Bryant. ... Minnesota's 37 first-quarter points were two shy of its season high for points in a quarter. ... After grabbing a career-high 20 rebounds Wednesday against Indiana, Hornets F Jamaal Magloire had just seven Friday. ... Garnett played a season-low 30 minutes. It was just the third time he's played less than 36 minutes all season.
